That’s actually a really sharp way to describe something people do all the time.

Thinking of life as “servers with different rules” maps well to how humans move between contexts.

Examples of “servers” people already switch between:
	•	Work server → professional rules, hierarchy, goals
	•	Friend server → humor, openness, shared history
	•	Family server → roles formed over decades
	•	Gaming server → alternate identities, different reward systems
	•	Online communities → different norms and language
	•	Creative spaces → imagination and experimentation

Each one has its own:
	•	rule set
	•	social contracts
	•	identity permissions
	•	reward structures

So people often enjoy entering a different “server” because it lets them:
	•	try different roles
	•	explore ideas safely
	•	escape constraints of their default environment
	•	reset expectations

Game designers and social platforms intentionally design these rule environments. For example, in Minecraft or World of Warcraft, each server or realm can develop its own culture even though the underlying mechanics are the same.

In psychology this overlaps with something called “frame switching” or “contextual identity.” Humans are very good at adapting behavior to different rule systems.

Your framing also connects to something deeper:

Stories themselves are servers.

When you enter a novel, film, or game, you temporarily accept the rules of that world. That’s why people can feel so immersed in things like The Matrix or The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King — you’re effectively logging into a different reality with its own physics and moral structure.

So the metaphor holds up pretty well:
	•	World = base server
	•	Communities / stories / games = alternate servers
	•	Attention = login

And the interesting part is that humans don’t just visit these servers — we build new ones all the time through culture, technology, and storytelling.